        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/12/1:643",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "What are the four? Here, bhikkhus, in regard to the body a bhikkhu abides contemplating the body, ardent, clearly knowing, and mindful, free from desires and discontent in regard to the world. In regard to feelings he abides contemplating feelings, ardent, clearly knowing, and mindful, free from desires and discontent in regard to the world. In regard to the mind he abides contemplating the mind, ardent, clearly knowing, and mindful, free from desires and discontent in regard to the world. In regard to dhammas he abides contemplating dhammas, ardent, clearly knowing, and mindful, free from desires and discontent in regard to the world.",
            "notes": "The Four Foundations",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/12/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T00:55:25.745Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "ibujPNxZYsPYf-pzAKAaZg"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/14/1:571",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "Ardent implies a balanced and sustained application of effort. But ardent also suggests warmth of feeling, a passionate and strong enthusiasm or devotion because we realize the value and importance of something. When the Buddha says that a bhikkhu (all of us on the path) abides ardently, he is urging us to take great care, with continuity and perseverance, in what we do",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/14/2/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T00:55:56.807Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "CvK9KhIIsdwAGP_p0as7TQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/22/1:131",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "One way to cultivate ardency is to reflect on the purpose of our practice, realizing that the Dharma is a jewel of priceless value.",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/22/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T00:56:29.116Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "H2X_AaqmK8D3ZzRQ9h3D6Q"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/22/1:449",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "understanding the mind is the same as understanding the Dharma, and that realizing the deepest truths of the mind is the attainment of awakening.",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/22/1:304",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T00:56:52.051Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "pOyO94K3m-jpAgjVnkSSyQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/26/6/2/1:1",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "Ask yourself how many of the billions of inhabitants of this planet have any idea of how rare it is to have been born as a human being. How many of those who understand the rarity of human birth ever think of using that chance to practice the Dharma? How many of those who think of practice actually do? How many of those who start continue? . . . But once you see the unique opportunity that human life can bring, you will definitely direct all your energy into reaping its true worth by putting the Dharma into practice.2",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/26/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T00:57:38.226Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "SiCeGsxcTmH9CqJ6EUCg4g"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/184/1:455",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "The third reflection that arouses ardor in our practice is the understanding of the law of karma. This is the fundamental and essential understanding that all of our volitional actions—of body, speech, and mind — bear fruit depending on the motivation associated with them. Actions rooted in greed, hatred, or ignorance bring unpleasant results. Actions rooted in nongreed, nonhatred, and nondelusion bring many different kinds of happiness and wellbeing.",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/184/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:00:32.073Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "oP8qX4eC4JBMtTs2keYfWQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/194/1:413",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "As we’re about to act, or when thoughts or emotions are predominant, do we remember to investigate and reflect on our motivation? Do we ask ourselves, “Is this act or mind state skillful or unskillful? Is this something to cultivate or abandon? Where is this motivation leading? Do I want to go there?”",
            "spine_index": 7,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter01.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/194/1:111",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:02:14.799Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "1. Ardency: The Long-Enduring Mind"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "Wbh2ZknxFP4Ictu1Tn6sKw"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/12/1:328",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "With clear comprehension, we know the purpose and appropriateness of what we’re doing; we understand the motivations behind our actions.",
            "notes": "SAMPAJAÑÑA ",
            "spine_index": 8,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter02.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/12/1:192",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:03:16.719Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "2. Clearly Knowing: Cultivating Clear Comprehension"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "WavXRwDtfLEzAIuGcnqGeQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/14/1:569",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "How does our practice benefit others? How does feeling our breath or taking a mindful step help anyone else? It happens in several ways. The more we understand our own minds, the more we understand everyone else. We increasingly feel the commonality of our human condition, of what creates suffering and how we can be free.",
            "spine_index": 8,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter02.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/14/1:250",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:19:37.315Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "2. Clearly Knowing: Cultivating Clear Comprehension"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "zSVXSmd97kFRI9n2ldqfSQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/34/1:142",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "“the five spiritual faculties”: faith, energy, mindfulness, concentration, and wisdom",
            "notes": "The Five Spiritual Faculties\n",
            "spine_index": 9,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter03.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/34/1:57",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:23:58.868Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "3. Mindfulness: The Gateway to Wisdom"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "lw4FFrzBeru-HRad7pXUTQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/36/1:335",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "Mindfulness makes us aware when any of them are deficient or in excess; for example, it balances faith and wisdom, energy and concentration. When we have too much faith, we can become dogmatic, attached to our own views. And we can see all too often how this blind belief leads to so much conflict and suffering in the world.\n\nWhen faith is not balanced with wisdom, we can also become overly enthusiastic about our meditation experiences. There is a state called “pseudo-nirvāna.” This is when our insight is developing, but in our enthusiasm we forget to be mindful, and then, because of our attachment to these very states, they become corruptions of insight.",
            "notes": "Balancing the five spiritual faculties",
            "spine_index": 9,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter03.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/34/1:261",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:24:47.332Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "3. Mindfulness: The Gateway to Wisdom"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "ioxhgQIDbkPBPF9ZS0b0Kg"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/46/1:660",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "our aim should be not to follow the heart but to train the heart. All of us have a mix of motivations; not everything in our hearts is wise or wholesome. The great power of mindful discernment allows us to abandon what is unwholesome and to cultivate the good. This discernment is of inestimable value for our happiness and wellbeing.",
            "spine_index": 9,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter03.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/46/1:326",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:26:21.461Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "3. Mindfulness: The Gateway to Wisdom"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "BtOL3qO29gni6ZlCwmyDww"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/70/1:622",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "In the Dzogchen tradition, this is called fabricated mindfulness, and is similar, perhaps, to what in the Theravāda Abhidhamma is called prompted consciousness. This is when, either by reflection or determination of the will, we deliberately endeavor to generate a certain state. There is another kind of mindfulness that is unprompted. When it is well cultivated, it arises spontaneously through the force of its own momentum. No particular effort is required. It’s all just happening by itself. In this state of effortless awareness, we can further discern the presence or absence of a reference point of observation, a sense of someone observing or being mindful.",
            "spine_index": 9,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter03.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/70/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-04T01:29:38.959Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "The Four Qualities of Mind",
                "3. Mindfulness: The Gateway to Wisdom"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "PMda6waR4C0NJ_RR3xz2Ug"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/16/4/2/1:1",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "“Bhikkhus, when anyone has not developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra finds an opportunity and a support. . . .”1\n\n“Bhikkhus, when anyone has developed and cultivated mindfulness of the body, Māra cannot find an opportunity or a support. . . .”2",
            "spine_index": 15,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter07.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/14/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
