        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/40/1:1063",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "All of this is summarized in the dharma statement, “Movement masks dukkha.” It’s worth investigating this to see for ourselves what drives the many movements we make during the day.",
            "spine_index": 16,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter08.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/40/1:882",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T00:54:35.007Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "8. Mindfulness of Postures"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "zqwlw0UDkgaMCfHe8HTPiQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/44/1:607",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "We see that there’s no one behind this process to whom it is all happening, only the pairwise progression of knowing and object rolling on.",
            "spine_index": 16,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter08.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/44/1:468",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T00:56:55.962Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "8. Mindfulness of Postures"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "aoi95OaghChLyqxeFNEsUg"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/52/1:214",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "The purpose of all our practice is to purify the mind of obstructive, unskillful states—in the Buddha’s words, “to abandon ill will and hatred, and to abide with a mind compassionate for the welfare of all beings.”",
            "spine_index": 16,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter08.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/52/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T00:59:50.132Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "8. Mindfulness of Postures"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "583kJJ0S3oncsjpKWOc87g"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/12/1:278",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "“Clearly knowing,” the translation of the Pali word sampajañña, is sometimes translated as “clear comprehension.” Clearly knowing means seeing precisely or seeing thoroughly, with all of the five spiritual faculties (confidence, energy, mindfulness, concentration, and wisdom) in balance.",
            "notes": "Sampajanna and the Five Spiritual Faculties",
            "spine_index": 17,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter09.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/12/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "blue"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:02:37.781Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "9. Mindfulness of Activities"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "VDms-m4EVJ1-0eVv1Zcd1g"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/20/1:163",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "The first way of training is clearly knowing the purpose of doing an action before we do it, understanding whether or not it is of benefit to ourselves and others.",
            "notes": "Pace is critical",
            "spine_index": 17,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter09.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/20/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:03:18.368Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "9. Mindfulness of Activities"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "JnnLL8FmsVikwPumc95gFA"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/20/1:687",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "Because our motivations are often subtle and hard to see—they are often mixed or are a series of conflicting motivations—it takes a lot of honesty, clarity, and mindfulness to see them clearly, to know the inner purpose behind our actions.",
            "spine_index": 17,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter09.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/20/1:448",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:03:38.093Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "9. Mindfulness of Activities"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "uRUJ1EZCoP8M0Z333k7geA"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/26/1:693",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "We might be feeling tired or frustrated, and then this kindly voice arises in the mind: “I’ve done enough. I’ve been working really hard. Let me take a little rest.” Sometimes we do need rest, but sometimes the kindly voice is just that aspect of sloth and torpor that retreats from difficulties.",
            "spine_index": 17,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter09.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/26/1:397",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:05:42.056Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "9. Mindfulness of Activities"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "ccHmdLN14kjxt1K-TpBDrg"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/28/1:302",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "This aspect of clear comprehension—seeing the purpose of our actions and whether they are of benefit or not—rests on our understanding the ethical dimensions of mindfulness. This is the discernment of wholesome or unwholesome mind states and actions, which lead respectively to happiness or suffering. ",
            "spine_index": 17,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter09.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/28/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:06:11.734Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "9. Mindfulness of Activities"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "R392OG8V_YUBe0KuY4a6zA"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/48/1:706",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "The famous thirteenth-century Japanese Zen master Dogen expressed it this way in the Genjo Koan: “What is the way of the Buddha? It is to study the self. What is the study of the self? It is to forget the self. To forget the self is to be Enlightened by all things.”",
            "spine_index": 17,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter09.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/48/1:440",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "blue"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:08:37.700Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "9. Mindfulness of Activities"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "fXv2aiYhEK-3FwFJlcjAQA"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/58/1:547",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "In meditation, we move from the concept of body to the awareness of the body as a changing energy field. On this level, the sense of the body as being something solid and substantial disappears.",
            "notes": "The Etheric body",
            "spine_index": 18,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter10.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/58/1:353",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "yellow"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:15:55.785Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "10. Mindfulness of Physical Characteristics"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "ZUgh9BitRLWPdLLRDxY8LQ"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/96/4/2/1:1",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "Dry out that which is past, let there be nothing for you in the future. If you do not grasp at anything in the present you will go about at peace. One who, in regard to this entire mind/body complex, has no cherishing of it as “mine,” and who does not grieve for what is non-existent truly suffers no loss in the world. For that person there is no thought of anything as “this is mine” or “this is another’s”; not finding any state of ownership, and realizing, “nothing is mine,” he does not grieve.7",
            "spine_index": 18,
            "spine_name": "OEBPS/xhtml/Chapter10.html",
            "start_cfi": "/2/4/96/1:0",
            "style": {
                "kind": "color",
                "type": "builtin",
                "which": "blue"
            },
            "timestamp": "2025-05-12T01:20:50.334Z",
            "toc_family_titles": [
                "Mindfulness of the Body",
                "10. Mindfulness of Physical Characteristics"
            ],
            "type": "highlight",
            "uuid": "MS2GH0s5cdInqwM7VPEFJg"
        },
        {
            "book_id": 3,
            "end_cfi": "/2/4/104/1:265",
            "format": "EPUB",
            "highlighted_text": "Those who believe in things can be helped through various kinds of practice, through skillful means—but those who fall into the abyss of emptiness find it almost impossible to re-emerge, since there seem to be no handholds, no steps, no gradual progression, nothing to do",
            "notes": "The Abyss of Emptiness",
